  "2026-07-12T06:14:58.724Z",maintainer-agent,"Second live occurrence 2026-07-12: pm-telemetry-postgres restarted ~04:00 (host maintenance window; container Up 8h vs worker Up 8d), worker logged continuous worker_insert_failed:the connection is closed, pm.telemetry.events backlogged to 111,382 messages / 1 consumer while Postgres kept serving reads. Remediation applied: docker compose restart telemetry-worker → consumer reattached, queue draining. This defect now has a repeatable operational cost on every Postgres restart — reconnect-with-backoff in the worker insert path remains the fix; consider raising priority."
body: "## Context\nIncident 2026-06-09/10 on the remote telemetry stack: pm-telemetry-postgres restarted; pm-telemetry-worker kept the dead connection and failed every insert ('worker_insert_failed: the connection is closed') for ~24h. RabbitMQ retained all 15,778 backed-up events (no data loss); manual `docker restart pm-telemetry-worker` drained the backlog in ~2 min.\n\n## Fix (remote stack, scripts/prod/telemetry on the host — NOT in this repo's tracked files)\n1. Worker reconnect/retry with backoff on closed Postgres connection instead of failing forever.\n2. Container healthcheck failing on repeated insert errors so docker auto-restarts.\n3. Optional alert when queue depth grows abnormally (Grafana panel already exists).\nStanding rule: never write host IPs/tokens into tracked files; verify via scripts/prod/telemetry/check-stack-health.sh.\n\n## Definition of done\nKill-postgres drill: worker reconnects unaided and drains the queue; healthcheck restarts a wedged worker; drill evidence recorded here (counts before/after)."
